In Java, there are two ways to compare strings: the == operator and the equals() method.

The == operator compares the references of two objects, while the equals() method compares the values of two objects.

When comparing strings with the == operator, you are actually comparing the references of the strings, not their values. This means that if two strings are created with the same value but with different references, they will not be considered equal when compared with the == operator.

For example:

```java
String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = "Hello";
System.out.println(s1 == s2); // true

String s3 = new String("Hello");
String s4 = new String("Hello");
System.out.println(s3 == s4); // false
```

In this example, `s1` and `s2` have the same value and reference, so when compared with the == operator, they are considered equal. However, `s3` and `s4` have different references even though they have the same value, so when compared with the == operator, they are considered unequal.

On the other hand, when comparing strings with the equals() method, you are actually comparing their values. This means that even if two strings have different references but the same value, they will be considered equal when compared with the equals() method.

For example:

```java
String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = "Hello";
System.out.println(s1.equals(s2)); // true

